More speculatively, we could use the information from ghost introgression to reconstruct certain characteristics of extinct lineages.This is nicely illustrated by a recent study that reconstructed the putative appearance of Denisovans.https://t.co/S1Kh4Y5F3H13/15

The reticulated nature of the evolutionary process has important consequences for macroevolutionary studies that generally assume a fixed species tree. Not taking into account the ghost introgression events might lead to errors in the reconstruction of trait evolution.12/15 https://t.co/bC0EfFPtdJ

The observation of ghost introgression suggests that the Tree of Life might be even more reticulated than expected, questioning whether even phylogenetic networks will be able to capture these complex evolutionary patterns.https://t.co/EUNiwmTqj711/15

Ghost introgression between two species might contribute to increased divergence and potentially reproductive isolation between those species and other related species, leading to rapid speciation.See for instance this paperhttps://t.co/UTNZWoMLnJ10/15

During population expansion, individuals might interbreed with other species, rapidly acquiring locally adapted loci and outcompeting the local populations which consequently go extinct. Hence, ghost introgression might help explain some of successful colonizations...9/15 https://t.co/RF9W25m2ie

Just like "normal" introgression, ghost introgression can result in the exchange of adaptive alleles. This probably happened with wild boars during their expansion across Asia.https://t.co/av224twNbR8/15

Finally, different demographic models can be compared in a statistical framework to confirm or reject the existence of ghost introgression.For example, a recent study on human ghost introgression combined ABC modelling with deep learning.https://t.co/xy6lB0AAPz7/15

Signatures of ghost introgression can be limited to the nuclear genome where they might become apparent as highly divergent haplotypes.This is nicely illustrated by a study on bonobos.https://t.co/QfjpwSPUEgWhich I also covered on my bloghttps://t.co/XO8qeT9aqW6/15
This approach was used to find ghost introgression in Phylloscopus warblers.You can read my blog posthttps://t.co/qvmwM5nKK7Or check the original paperhttps://t.co/jWlJ4hordg5/15

A first clue for the presence of ghost introgression comes from analyses of mtDNA or plastid DNA. Patterns of deep divergence in organellar DNA in combination with shallow nuclear divergence might be due to mitochondrial or plastid capture from an extinct species.4/15

Given that fossilization is a rare phenomenon and that most fossils do not yield sufficient genetic material, we are probably missing numerous ghost introgression events. Luckily, we can use other clues to find ghost DNA in modern genomes, as illustrated in this figure.3/15 https://t.co/kbtZZesHTP

First, what is ghost introgression?It concerns ancient introgression events that left traces of extinct species in modern genomes.Some studies used ancient DNA from fossils to show ghost introgression. See for example this study on cave bears.https://t.co/MFgfrYeM7D2/15

So all the best, from the depth of my heart, to the Clinicians/Kliniker/Clinicien/Terapeuta/clinico etc and the Enfermeros/Infirmiers/Krankenpfleger/infermieri/Nurses etc across Europe and the world.

And in that meantime the health services of the world have to handle the horrible end points of this virus. I have enough clinical colleagues (and on enough Slack channels with them) just to have ultimate respect for everyone who is doing this - in every healthcare system.

Mid/long term - the exit strategy is science - changing viral or human biology in infection. Plenty of reasons to be hopeful, almost confident of a result, "just" the timing of changing things is going to be hard and in the meantime we have to *radically* change behaviour.

It really is virus vs humans here; it is not about countries or regions or politics or classes. For the people who rage against this - please expect to be muted by me at the least. I caution trying to find too much blame or understanding in the run up to this.

It's worth pointing out again that the virus really doesn't care about human politics or processes - it just has a new host it can expand in. The changes in behaviour in humans can radically change the rate of infection - which is our only option at the moment.
I get the (b) point - humans are humans after all and for some people talking about this crisis using their own comfortable frame of reference is just ... very human.

...or it will be the day that history looks back on with the full-lipped, shameful head shakes reserved for Watergate or Wounded Knee. This *will* be painful for it to work. And, *if* it works, it will seem like we did it all for nothing. But, there will be a lot less funerals.

And that right there will be the inflection point. A week from today -- Monday, March 30th, 2020 -- will be the day that history will look back & nod with a pursed-lipped, tight-jawed, prideful smile the way we look back at Rosie the Riveter or the safe splashdown of Apollo 13...

The understanding that this will impact your best laid plans, your livelihood, or your re-election campaign is beginning to blow away the mystique of the never-ending 'snow day', gently first, but with a steady rising. By next week, you'll be full-on pissed.

But now, at the very moment that reality is setting in, the talk of giving up on everything that was so critical just days ago echoes through the most hallowed halls of our government. The memes and selfies have lost their 'pandemic chic'. Your kids are driving you nuts.

I myself indulged in more than a few think-pieces on how we all might use this time to get back to basics and better ourselves through what truly matters...family, neighbors, nature, art & creativity, exercising, reading & learning, or just being still.

It was the same revelry associated with a 'snow day' off from school or work. But it was a whole week, w/ the promise to extend for many more. And everyone collectively woo-sah'd @ the chance to finally have a break from the breathless, accelerating pace & pressure of modern life

You can see it happening already -- the cracks in the dam. Last week was sorta "fun" for average folks. "Oh boy, a pandemic! They say we gotta stay home. Quick, pose for our 'social distance' selfie! Make cute toilet paper memes!" Everybody promised to patriotically do their part

FOUR: Practice empathy. Taking care of yourself &others during this time is so important. Just because we can't hang out in groups doesn't mean we can't text a colleague, video call a friend, or drop some milk off for a neighbor in need. Human compassion will help get us through.

THREE: Tracking viral spread. The vital testing work being performed by the BCCDC is helping provide a better understanding of how COVID-19 is spreading in communities around BC. This information can help determine how best to combat the spread and keep us safe.

TWO: Maintain social distance. Avoid going out for anything other than essential tasks & when you do, avoid standing closer than 2m to people to reduce the risk of exposure. We know not everyone can stay home from their jobs & we are grateful for those performing essential roles!

ONE: Clean hands! The importance of washing hands with soap and water to help stop the spread of COVID-19 cannot be overstated. Wash those hands after touching surfaces that could be contaminated, and especially before touching your face.

I was shunted through a door that ended up leading to a large lift, heading down to the boarding gate with 3 others, and one terminal staff. The lift stopped because it was unbalanced; I & the terminal staff member moved into the centre of the lift.It started again.I woke up.

One of those benefits was "fixing undesirable conditions", which made something click in my head."I have a pre-existing medical condition with my heart!"That was the straw that broke them. They cleared up the bedding and wires, then told me I had 10 mins to board.

I asked someone I knew who was sitting beside me if they knew what the wires and black passed mats were for. They replied, "An electric chair?" "Close..." was the reply from the terminal staff. Then they started listing the benefits of electric shock therapy.

I ended up at an alternate Chinese terminal of Singapore airport, at a place that reminded me of the Blue ridge ferry, and was asked to participate in an electro-shock therapy trial while I waited for my next flight. I pleaded for them not to do it, but they wouldn't budge.

With the above in mind, we can all practice appropriate work-from-home distancing.

10. Coffee shops get busy! Every few days, simulate the no-available-tables experience by taking your muffin or coffee to go and instead resorting to your Plan B: your five-monitor home office setup with a gigabit connection and 300-square-foot standing desk.

9. Consider ordering a lock for your bathroom; key, keypad, whatever. If you go with a key, affix it to some large, wonky item. Leave it with your cat. Politely ask your cat for the key when appropriate. Bonus points if you include signage directing employees to wash hands.
8. Do not order outside food. Remember, it's muffins and coffee only. See 6, supra. Oh, you thought this was one of those coffee shops with sandwiches? Sorry. They ran out of bread yesterday.
7. If you have a car and a driveway, consider moving your car to a metered space. Remember to feed the meter! But make sure to forget at least once.
6. Make sure to wander into your kitchen every hour or so and get a food or drink item out of guilt. Maybe coffee. Maybe a muffin! Water does not count.

5. Make sure you ask someone to watch your computer, etc., when you go use the restroom. Maybe you have a roommate you can trust! Alternatively, kindly ask your dog. (Do *not* trust your cat to watch your stuff.) Or hire someone to watch it over Skype.

4. For a long-term situation, consider changing your WiFi password each day. Give the new password to your dog. Ask your dog for the password, but make sure you get some food first. WiFi is for customers only! Bonus points if you throttle your connection speed.

3. Place a speaker in the corner of the room and direct it to play something idiosyncratic. Maybe some electronic/indie artist, I don't know. Just so long as it's slightly distracting and you aren't familiar with it. Do not let yourself change this music.

I predict some difficult times ahead in the immediate future. Though, I have some hopes that the COVID-19 pandemic will bring the best out of humanity, and that this crisis will act as a catalyst for us to deal more effectively, together, with future global challenges. (15/15)

Pandemics like this one have been looming for millennia, and covid-19 won't be the last humanity will face. We have been caught napping and we now have to deal from a position of weakness with a difficult situation that could have been, in principle, largely avoidable. (14/15)

As such, I have little doubt we're heading for a 'suppression' approach to covid-19. Given the many unknowns and the difficult moral implications, it probably makes sense to try to address the most urgent issue. There are times when tactics might trump strategy. (13/15)

There may actually be no choice. Politically, but also morally and ethically, any option leading to a heavy death toll over the coming months, but offering the possible prospect of maximising long-term life-expectancy would be a difficult sell. (12/15)

The report can be read in many different ways, but fundamentally, it confirms that we are facing a series of uncomfortable options within a continuum ranging from paying a heavy death toll right now vs. an uncertain and possibly even worse future. (11/15)

Though, the report is in fact fairly balanced and acknowledges (but doesn‚Äôt model) the extreme economic damage that a 'suppression' strategy would inflict on the economy (and by extrapolation to health, education and longevity). (10/15)

The report has been widely interpreted as being supportive of the 'suppression' strategy, which may entail a country-wide lockdown for up to 18 months. This may be a slight misunderstanding of a sophisticated piece, which acknowledges there is no easy solution. (9/15)

Two basic strategies are considered: (a) 'mitigation', which focuses on slowing but not necessarily stopping epidemic spread (i.e. 'Herd Immunity"), and (b) 'suppression', which aims to reduce case numbers to low levels and maintaining that situation indefinitely. (8/15)

One key question was how the phosphorylation at the two sites are coupled. Experimentally phosphorylation of Y88 promotes a second phosphorylation at Y74, but these are located on opposite sites. Joao's simulations of Y74 binding with Y88 or pY88 suggest a mechanism for this 4/n

Positively binding sites are active in less cell types, as expected if pleiotropy limits adaptive evolution. https://t.co/Z0nwO6B2tC

As expected, outside of brain, the top adaptive regulatory evolution systems are male reproduction, immune and endocrine systems. Brain differs in not having evidence of adaptation at protein level, unlike the others.
And the result is... most positive selection on regulatory sequences active in brain cell types üòÄWe have less data in mouse, but they do not share this pattern. üê≠ https://t.co/Adm4Jfd7lW

Because we use experimental ChIP-seq, we can analyse separately regulatory sites per organ, tissue, or cell type, if there is data.@ENCODE_NIH provides CTCF ChIP-seq in 29 adult human tissues or primary cell types. ‚úÖ

There have been previous attempts to address this of course, but (i) they had the method limitations specified earlier, and (ii) they usually lacked the capacity to link results to activity in specific organs.

OK, so we have a method to detect positive selection on regulatory sites.Now we can address a big question in evolutionary biology: the prediction that adaptation in human evolution has largely been in gene regulation, especially human brain evolution.https://t.co/ywSgFr50Kq

Many lives will be lost if and when the covid-19 pandemic spreads. Even more lives will be lost if and when the global economy tanks. I find it difficult to model a plausible scenario where we will not be facing both. (4/4)

The 'wickedness' of the Covid-19 pandemic problem stems from the fact that there is no such choice as either saving lives or the economy, as many people seem to believe. The economy is the very reason why life expectancy is lower in say Afghanistan or Somalia than Italy or Japan.

Doing nothing is not acceptable and essentially any intervention I can think of, including 'flattening the curve measures' is likely to further worsen the situation by fuelling a second peak during the coming winter when current healthcare capacity will be further depleted. (2/4)

I have thought very long and hard about the best mitigation strategies for the Covid-19 pandemic over the last week ... and reached the conclusion this really is a 'wicked problem'. I believe anyone who believes there are simple fixes didn't think hard enough about it (1/4)

If you or a loved one is interested in learning more about what conditions might be treated with CRISPR or participating in a clinical trial, you can learn more here: https://t.co/WAhJ22hUTI (8/8)

If it works, this will be the first direct fix to a mutated gene. Traditional gene therapies work by adding an extra copy of a gene. CRISPR treatments for cancer and blood disorders use other strategies. Success here would be a major step forward in genetic medicine! (7/8)

They will also look for whether the CRISPR-Cas9 components or the virus used to deliver them provokes an immune response. Luckily, the eye is contained and less likely to have immune responses than most of the body. (6/8)

Researchers will monitor the patient-volunteer closely to see what percentage of photoreceptor cells are effectively edited, and whether it‚Äôs enough to restore vision. They expect to know within a few months if, and how much, vision will be restored. (5/8)

This is the 1st CRISPR treatment to be administered directly to a patient‚Äôs body. In other CRISPR treatments‚Äîfor cancer, sickle cell disease, & beta thalassemia‚Äîscientists edit the cells outside of the body and put them back in. This is injected directly into the eye. (4/8)

The CRISPR treatment for LCA10 makes a change to the patient‚Äôs faulty photoreceptor gene. If it works, the photoreceptors will make a full-size, functional protein instead of the short, broken version. (3/8)

Photoreceptor cells in the eye turn light into nerve signals that travel to the brain. In LCA10, a mutation in a photoreceptor gene makes a shortened, defective version of a crucial protein. Photoreceptors can no longer communicate between the eyes and the brain. üëÅÔ∏è üö´ üß† (2/8)

We hope this is useful, we welcome suggestions, and want to stress that these are scenarios of simplistic models. The actual outcome depends above all on what we do to prevent the spread of #COVID19.

The main outputs are graphs of cases, severe cases, critical cases, and cumulative fatalities. (show/hide lines by clicking on the legend). OECD average *total* hospital capacity (scaled to population) is indicated as a horizontal line. https://t.co/LlNIU3SZTt
The last column allows you to explore the effect of isolating specific age groups (reduction in exposure).

Our assumptions on severity are summarized in this table informed by data from China CDC. Most columns are editable and allow you to specify what fraction of cases show up in statistics, how many of those are severe, critical, and fatal (in a nested fashion). https://t.co/9wfTYGnU6k

To explore the effect of infection control measures, you can modify the graph in this panel. The value modulates the baseline parameters set above. Moving dots down implies more control: 1 corresponds to no control, 0 to avoiding all infections. https://t.co/mo3a4T9DaD

In addition, to estimate hospital bed demand, you can select the average length of a hospital stay. This applies to both regular and ICU beds additively. Presumed seasonal variation can also be adjusted.

The basic epidemiological parameters can be adjusted in this panel. You can set the annual average R0, the delay from infection to transmission, and the typical infectious period. These add up to a serial interval of 8 days in our defaults. https://t.co/S15zR9Hn8w

The default scenario is for a medium-size city in Switzerland with a fairly slow-spreading outbreak and strong infection control measures. You can adjust all parameters (sometimes a little fiddly, we are working on it). The population parameters can be adjusted in this panel: https://t.co/GiTrSxkLMO

Over the past few days, we (Ivan, @n_b_noll and I) developed a tool to explore scenarios for hospital demand in your community. Our prototype is here, still rough, we hope it's useful. We are sharing it early since the situation is developing so fast.https://t.co/WD97ih2240

My search and study focuses on continued pregnancies in particular. How do we help parents cope, heal, prepare, bond, hope, enjoy? What does that support look like? Who delivers it? Who catches those falling through the gaps?If you want to talk about this, please get in touch

And, I can't help but wonder - will my thesis be just another piece that brings to light the experience, yes it's novel due to the particular #congenitalanomaly and ambiguity. But... How do we move to action on the ground, support for people moving through a #prenataldiagnosis?

With one in 22 babies diagnosed with a major congenital anomaly, & the available literature showing that we must improve the emotional support for parents, whether they continue their pregnancies or not... I'm not sure why there is such a paucity when it comes to #interventions.

I've got to say, it's not looking good. I've found more studies about components of the experience and the effect on #mentalhealth. But interventions - how to actually help, what works, pathways of care, trials?... It's not looking good at this stage.

A need that goes beyond the time or session limited diagnostic/ prognostic or #geneticcounselling that is. The search was extensive, my screenshot is only a snippet. Over 5000 titles/abstracts reviewed in hope to find these studies. I'm still moving through the full-texts but..

I extended my #phdlife lit review thinking there must be intervention focused studies, there must be evidence abt how to support parents through a prenatal diagnosis of a congenital anomaly. I figured it must just be hiding as studies have shown the need for decades. https://t.co/AIKlB0eUPi

which level you choose is a trade-off between power and interpretability - on the entire gene level it's easy to interpret but you miss all those tiny cool TE insertions. On the k-mer level you have to do a ton of work to go from association to interpretation...

The interesting thing about the 8 B. napus pangenome PAV GWAS is that their associated PAV regions turned out to be PAV of TEs. it becomes a hierarchy, with k-mers at the bottom and entire genes (all exons) at the top, and you can choose on which level you want to run your GWAS

A bonus is that the miniature growth habit is caused by a set of recessive mutations. This means that as soon as I have that first plant, I can easily guarantee the seeds it produces will also grow out as miniatures.
Increasing the diversity available in miniature sized tomato plants has been a personal goal for several years.I'm very much looking forward to seeing what grows out this year.
The regular dwarfed plants are great sized for a home garden without large supports.The miniature dwarfed plants are sized just right to grow in a window-box or in a balcony railing flower-box.

Those hybrids were heterozygous for at least two dwarfing mutations. The seeds I saved will this year grow out to produce a range or different sized plants, hopefully with some interesting fruit colors.
Last year I grew out several tomato seeds that turned out to be hybrids. I had saved seeds the year before from a miniature variety called "Tiny Tim". The hybrids grew full sized. #PlantBreeding

40. MIPSWe learnt a bit of MIPS assembly when studying computer science at university. I liked the idea of a simple structured assembly, and have memories of enjoyment around both learning (as a student) and teaching MIPS (as a tutor).https://t.co/7FjSX3u6dd

39. AwkAlmost the entirety of my Awk experience has been in one-liners to manipulate text fields for bioinformatics. Awk works well for quick manipulation of tab-separated files.https://t.co/yATDB3f0yA

38. POV-RayMostly I was peeking over the shoulder of my friend while they were writing POV-Ray scenes. I did a couple of simple things (e.g. a ball on a plane), but I never really felt a pressing need to do 3D modelling until OpenSCAD came along.https://t.co/E6zVugGHYc

37. QuakeWorldI played a bit of Quake Team Fortress, and noticed that it's console had some programming functionality which was *almost* turing complete. I can't remember what I used it for, maybe timed messages.https://t.co/uH2DYVMz4v

36. HyperCardI have vague memories of a card-like language that we had to work with in high school, and I think it was probably HyperCard. Despite my enjoyment of visual languages it didn't grab my attention enough for me to remember it.https://t.co/cbIhdmkg4v

35. sh (including Csh, bash and dash)One-liner shell scripts make up the majority of my bioinformatics coding, but I've made and hacked a few longer script files. Shell scripts are all over the place on Linux systems, so it's helpful to understand them.https://t.co/AkUPEmQUhw

34. Visual BASICIt's a bit different from BASIC, and a bit more complex than VBA. I've mostly tinkered with other people's code rather than written my own applications, as I prefer Java  and R/Shiny... and getting scratched by a cat, for that matter.https://t.co/OZjvHcKLHS

33. EnigmaSpeaking of which, I might as well mention that as well. I haven't written any Enigma code from scratch, but I have tinkered a tiny bit with levels others have written, mostly to work out how I can solve them. It even has Tetris!https://t.co/f2c6zs0DD5

32. BrainfuckGiven that brainfuck is an esoteric / parody language, I feel fine stating that my biggest program written in it was created while playing the marble-rolling game Enigma.https://t.co/1NN8C5esqX

31. CI've written a couple of C programs, but most of my interaction involves modifying someone else's bioinformatics C code, which is a bit like walking on broken glass. It's mind-numbingly easy to write crashable C code without realising it.https://t.co/Y5wCjRLHWH

30. LispMost of my interaction with Lisp has been trying to get Emacs to work better. I get easily confused by the parentheses, and generally retreat to R or OpenSCAD, while reminding myself that I should really try to get the hang of Lisp some day.https://t.co/DzeW1u8Cl8

29. LogoI enjoy graphical languages, and was pleasantly surprised to discover in high school (as part of formal teaching) that Logo could also be used for knowledge-based systems (e.g. 20-questions).https://t.co/mIIUJYPILC

28. LilyPondLilyPond is to musical engraving as LaTeX is to writing. I've written / copied a couple of songs into LilyPond format. It's a bit fiddly, sometimes requiring a bit of web searching to get the right incantation, but it makes nice pictures.https://t.co/aFKue4UCqa

27. MapleWe learnt Maple as part of our university mathematics course, but I'd learnt it a few years earlier as part of a high-school extension course. I enjoyed watching our lecturer whip up some quick animations, and demonstrate integration solutions.https://t.co/AAP7GovIa7

26. PythonPython reminded me a bit of MATLAB in its array notation; I like the simplicity of array slicing. What I don't like is the way that copy-pasted code creates unintended effects due to indentation differences. I like my braces and semicolons!https://t.co/O3wdY2OQQE

25. MATLAB (and Octave)The idea of ultra-fast matrix manipulation, and succinct range slicing, was pleasing to me. Less so was the idea that a programming language could be commercialised.https://t.co/mpwgAzxRMS

24. OpenSCADOpenSCAD is declarative in a similar way to Prolog, but has the interesting idea that everything that is created is a representation of a 3D object. My computer science knowledge has helped in finding workarounds to some of its quirks.https://t.co/fqthwQSKTU

You may have noticed a bit of a theme with the last few tweets... I like growing plants from seed that aren't conventionally grown this way. Doing so lets me see unexpected diversity, which is an important step in starting a plant breeding project.

Finally, thank you to our awesome collaborators: @RMSahasrabudhe, @josh_schmidt1, and @AidaAndresStay tuned for more projects related to human duplications, gene regulation at SVs, and using zebrafish to test interesting genes!

Our analysis was conservative, and there is much more that can be mined from these data (including insertions and duplications). We are in the midst of generating an assembly with these combined datasets and would be excited to work with others that are developing new tools

We believe this represents the first nanopore sequencing of a chimpanzee (a western female) and, importantly, all our data is available for download (Illumina, ONT, bionano, and Hi-C) here: https://t.co/rupKap6yid
We also generated TAD maps directly comparing human and chimpanzee that show how inversions and deletion can perturb the chromatin landscape. https://t.co/3U1XYJYb8i

Coupled with RNA-seq and Hi-C data from LCLs and IPSCs (thank you to @Y_Gilad for sharing cell lines and published data), we found SVs to be enriched for differentially-expressed genes btwn human and chimpanzee and depleted for TAD boundaries, recapitulating work from others.

We applied Millefy to scRNA-seq of mESC and TNBC tumor cells and found cell-to-cell heterogeneity in antisense RNAs, enhancer RNAs, and 3' UTR lengths, which may be missed by conventional gene expression matrix analysis.

Read coverage reflects RNA transcription and processing events. After expression level quantification, information possessed by read coverage is lost. Thus, Millefy will complements dimension reduction methods, which map expression vectors to points in a low dimensional space.

Our paper "Millefy: visualizing cell-to-cell heterogeneity in read coverage of single-cell RNA sequencing datasets" is finally published! https://t.co/PH3rO2ytsX Highlights cell-to-cell heterogeneity in read coverage by w/ diffusion maps. Applied to ES and tumor cell data.
